      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "Rule-of-thumb from these data:\n- Precipitation requires the free-ion product [Ca^2+][C2O4^2−] ≳ Ksp. Because oxalate becomes the dianion mainly above its second pKa (pKa2 ≈ 3.8), the C2O4^2− fraction increases steeply across pH 3–4.\n- For equimolar totals C_T of Ca and oxalate (and ignoring activity corrections), precipitation is impossible if C_T < √Ksp ≈ 4×10^−5 M (~40 μM). Above this, the “onset pH” satisfies α2(pH) ≈ Ksp / C_T^2, where α2 is the fraction of total oxalate present as C2O4^2−.\n  - Example: at C_T = 0.1 mM, Ksp/C_T^2 ≈ 0.18, which corresponds to pH ≈ 3.2–3.3; at C_T = 1 mM it’s ≈ pH ~1–2; at very dilute levels (≤10 μM) precipitation cannot occur regardless of pH.",
